<PolicyLayout title="Code of Conduct" lastReviewed="July 2025">

<p>
  Everyone who represents Hope For Families — whether as paid staff, volunteer, trustee or placement student — is an
  ambassador for our values. This Code of Conduct sets out the standards of behaviour we expect so that our
  community remains safe, inclusive and welcoming for all.
</p>

<h2>1. Core Values</h2>
<p>Our work is guided by four values. Every person connected to Hope For Families is expected to uphold them:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Inclusion</strong> — We welcome everyone, regardless of background, faith, disability, gender, age or immigration status.</li>
  <li><strong>Empowerment</strong> — We treat participants as capable individuals with strengths, not as problems to be fixed.</li>
  <li><strong>Community</strong> — We build relationships based on trust and mutual respect.</li>
  <li><strong>Compassion</strong> — We listen, we care, and we serve with genuine warmth.</li>
</ul>

<h2>2. Professional Conduct</h2>
<p>All staff and volunteers must:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Arrive on time and fulfil their agreed commitments reliably.</li>
  <li>Act in a way that reflects positively on Hope For Families at all times, both in person and online.</li>
  <li>Follow instructions from line managers and session leaders.</li>
  <li>Raise concerns through the correct channels rather than airing grievances publicly.</li>
  <li>Maintain confidentiality about participants, colleagues and organisational matters.</li>
  <li>Complete mandatory training — including safeguarding — within the timeframe given.</li>
</ul>

<h2>3. Inclusion &amp; Respect</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Use inclusive, non-discriminatory language at all times. Never use terms that demean or stereotype any group.</li>
  <li>Actively challenge discriminatory behaviour or language if you witness it — or report it to a manager immediately.</li>
  <li>Respect cultural differences, including different communication styles, food practices and religious observances.</li>
  <li>Do not make assumptions about someone's background, abilities or situation.</li>
  <li>Ensure accessibility in sessions — be alert to language barriers and offer support appropriately.</li>
</ul>

<h2>4. Boundaries with Participants</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Maintain professional boundaries at all times. Friendly warmth is expected; personal relationships that cross professional lines are not.</li>
  <li>Do not share your personal phone number, email address or home address with participants.</li>
  <li>Do not connect with participants on personal social media accounts.</li>
  <li>Do not give or receive significant gifts from participants.</li>
  <li>Never be alone in an enclosed space with a child. Apply the two-adult rule wherever possible.</li>
  <li>Physical contact with children should be minimal, in public, and appropriate to the activity (e.g., a reassuring pat on the shoulder).</li>
</ul>

<h2>5. Social Media</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Do not post images of participants online without explicit written consent — this is especially important for images of children. Refer to our <a href="/policies/consent">Consent Policy</a>.</li>
  <li>Do not make public statements about Hope For Families on social media that have not been agreed with the management team.</li>
  <li>Do not engage in online arguments or post anything that could embarrass the organisation or harm community trust.</li>
  <li>If in doubt, don't post — ask a manager first.</li>
</ul>

<h2>6. Conflicts of Interest</h2>
<p>
  A conflict of interest arises when personal interests could influence — or be seen to influence — decisions made
  on behalf of Hope For Families. All staff, volunteers and trustees must:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Declare any personal, financial or professional interest that might conflict with their role.</li>
  <li>Withdraw from any decision-making process where a conflict exists.</li>
  <li>Never use their position to gain personal advantage or advantage for others they are connected to.</li>
</ul>

<h2>7. Confidentiality</h2>
<p>
  Many participants share sensitive information with us — about their health, family circumstances, immigration
  status or finances. This information:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Must only be shared on a need-to-know basis within the organisation.</li>
  <li>Must never be shared outside the organisation without the participant's consent, unless there is an overriding safeguarding concern.</li>
  <li>Must be stored and handled in accordance with our <a href="/policies/privacy-policy">Privacy Policy</a> and UK GDPR.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  Confidentiality is not absolute. If a disclosure suggests someone is at risk of harm, you must report this
  in line with our <a href="/policies/safeguarding">Safeguarding Policy</a> — even if the person asks you not to.
</p>

<h2>8. Breaches of This Code</h2>
<p>
  Breaches of this Code of Conduct will be taken seriously. Depending on the severity, a breach may result in:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>An informal reminder or formal warning.</li>
  <li>Suspension pending investigation.</li>
  <li>Termination of volunteering or employment.</li>
  <li>Referral to statutory agencies (e.g., Police Scotland or Disclosure Scotland) if the breach involves
  potential criminal conduct or a safeguarding failure.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  Anyone wishing to raise a concern about a colleague's conduct should speak to the Designated Safeguarding
  Officer or the Chair of Trustees in confidence.
</p>

